Movie: Chicken Run: Dawn of the Nugget
Review: Chicken Run: Dawn of the Nugget does not quite capture the magic of its predecessor, but 2000 was a simpler time. The Towers had not yet fallen. Mel Gibson could still voice a rooster (he's replaced here by Zachary Levi...another actor who has famously never been problematic). It's 2023 now, and it was nice to return to that simpler time for an hour and forty minutes. How much of the coastline will sink under the waves in my lifetime? Who's…

Fuck the haters. I mean, no one else in the theater had as much fun as we did, but they just can’t see the magic. Script is dumb as a sack of bricks; the bulk of it is giving himbos (and Nicole Kidman) the opportunity to say the word “orichalcum” as often as possible. Yes, it’s spelled like that. Aquaman doesn’t even have an arc this time around. But it’s the best underwater imagery and action this side of Way…

I would love to be able to say that this is a very fun, sweet little movie. And in many ways, it is. But it also commits a cardinal sin of positioning itself as a prequel to a much better movie. WONKA begins and ends with Pure Imagination, a more memorable song than any of the movie’s original numbers. Chalamet is written and dressed to evoke a more innocent incarnation of Gene Wilder’s performance, and the constant comparison that invites…
A shockingly great double feature with Poor Things. A perfectly delicate portrayal of what can happen when a Hollywood actress wreaks havoc on a completely innocent family.

Lanthimos, at his funniest (but also, somehow, least stressful), embarks on a vivid odyssey that's fucked beyond the pale. At times makes highly questionable choices, but I largely loved it. Stone is unsurprisingly at an all-time high here, but the movie is bound by a Mark Ruffalo performance that, frankly, society is not prepared for.

The closest comparison I can make to this is if a French director got their hands on The Crown or a movie like Elizabeth. The ensemble remains the same, but Miss Piggy plays the Queen, and she does not have a script. It would make for a more interesting viewing experience, and certainly a more fun one, but not necessarily a better one.There’s an irreverence here that fascinates me, and is largely refreshing for this kind of biopic. The most damning thing about The Marvels is that after, I don’t know, twenty projects since Endgame, the one that starts to bring characters together and pay things off has one of the most incoherent scripts the MCU has ever done. This movie feels like it’s missing at least half an hour, but I’m not sure if adding that back in would help. I could write about the plot for a thousand words but I’m fairly certain it would melt…

An eight hour exercise in setting up a villain from a second show to be the new villain of a third show, all with a cast of previously established characters I have no reason to care about. Breaks several unspoken rules of the larger Star Wars world, in ways that I’m told that the animated show it’s based on already did. But if this was designed to be a live action Star Wars Rebels season 5, which, surprise, it is,…
